WEBVTT

00:07.833 --> 00:10.749
<i>narrator: Previously on</i> <i>
"The Thing About Pam."</i>

00:10.793 --> 00:12.882
This time chemo wasn't bad.

00:12.925 --> 00:14.710
I feel kinda good.

00:14.753 --> 00:17.147
So what happened to Betsy?

00:17.191 --> 00:19.236
Some kind of accident
or something?

00:19.280 --> 00:21.195
She's not accidentally dead.

00:21.238 --> 00:23.153
<i>She's not naturally dead.</i>

00:23.197 --> 00:25.242
Some lady on Sumac
got stabbed,

00:25.286 --> 00:27.897
20, maybe 60 times.

00:27.940 --> 00:30.204
Textbook spousal homicide.

00:30.247 --> 00:33.163
<i>He was kinda not nice</i> <i>
verbally to her.</i>

00:33.207 --> 00:35.687
Real aggressive.

00:35.731 --> 00:37.515
Pam is a good person.

00:37.559 --> 00:40.214
And I just don't care
for his type.

00:40.257 --> 00:44.044
<i>[sinister music]</i>

00:44.087 --> 00:47.482
<i>narrator: A grieving family</i> <i>
is a family in need,</i>

00:47.525 --> 00:50.876
<i>and Pam is all helping hands.</i>

00:50.920 --> 00:53.357
<i>♪</i>

00:53.401 --> 00:56.056
<i>Who would think</i> <i>
such a nice lady</i>

00:56.099 --> 00:59.102
<i>was there to help herself?</i>

00:59.146 --> 01:00.973
God, such a hassle.

01:01.017 --> 01:03.889
All those people in your hair
on a day like this.

01:03.933 --> 01:05.804
You need a pick-me-up.

01:07.197 --> 01:08.546
Aunt Tammy,

01:08.590 --> 01:10.418
I've been trying
to call my dad all day

01:10.461 --> 01:12.289
and he's not answering.

01:12.333 --> 01:15.118
Bet they took his phone.

01:15.162 --> 01:18.426
Why--why would they
take his phone?

01:20.167 --> 01:21.385
I'm gonna go find him.

01:21.429 --> 01:24.301
Sweetie, sweetie.
Why don't you stay?

01:24.345 --> 01:25.389
No. He's--he's all alone.

01:25.433 --> 01:28.131
Two sugars, right?

01:28.175 --> 01:30.307
I'll just have
a little cream. Thanks.

01:30.351 --> 01:32.004
I wouldn't worry too much
about Russ.

01:32.048 --> 01:35.095
You know, they always
look at the husband first.

01:36.705 --> 01:38.402
Big surprise.

01:39.534 --> 01:41.492
You're not surprised
they got Russ?

01:43.059 --> 01:44.930
He could be scary.

01:44.974 --> 01:46.236
Oh, I know.

01:46.280 --> 01:48.499
One time he said,
"You women are such asses."

01:48.543 --> 01:50.197
And I was like, "Excuse me,

01:50.240 --> 01:51.937
"just trying to get directions
to the house.

01:51.981 --> 01:54.157
No need for that."

01:54.201 --> 01:55.593
One time he chased
my ex-boyfriend

01:55.637 --> 01:58.205
out the house
with a baseball bat.

01:58.248 --> 01:59.728
- No.
- Yeah.

01:59.771 --> 02:01.817
Lord knows
Russ isn't perfect,

02:01.860 --> 02:04.776
but don't go around saying
that the police have got him.

02:04.820 --> 02:08.215
We just don't need the whole
town talking like he--

02:08.258 --> 02:11.435
like he--

02:11.479 --> 02:13.350
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
Oh, there will be talk.</i>

02:13.394 --> 02:15.439
<i>A whole lot of talk</i>

02:15.483 --> 02:19.226
<i>from some more than others.</i>

02:19.269 --> 02:22.185
<i>[sinister music]</i>

02:22.229 --> 02:25.362
<i>♪</i>

02:26.624 --> 02:30.411
<i>What does a lie</i> <i>
look like anyway?</i>

02:30.454 --> 02:34.371
<i>Is it a line on a graph?</i>

02:34.415 --> 02:37.200
Did you kill Betsy Faria?

02:37.244 --> 02:39.507
No.

02:39.550 --> 02:43.641
Do you know
who killed Betsy Faria?

02:43.685 --> 02:47.079
No.

02:47.123 --> 02:50.344
Is today December 28th, 2011?

02:52.128 --> 02:57.133
Yes.

02:57.177 --> 03:02.007
I think we got what we need.

03:02.051 --> 03:05.010
<i>[unsettling music]</i>

03:05.054 --> 03:09.450
<i>♪</i>

03:09.493 --> 03:11.713
[machinery beeping]
[exhales deeply]

03:11.756 --> 03:18.676
<i>♪</i>

03:22.289 --> 03:25.901
- - I, uh--
- I--
- [chuckling]

03:25.944 --> 03:29.034
I need to see my dad,
Russ Faria.

03:29.078 --> 03:31.559
Um, he's gonna be back there
for a while.

03:31.602 --> 03:33.604
I wouldn't bother waiting.

03:37.913 --> 03:39.523
Hi,
I'm Russ Faria's daughter.

03:39.567 --> 03:41.873
I'm looking for my dad and--

03:41.917 --> 03:44.833
[indistinct chatter]

03:48.184 --> 03:51.100
<i>[unsettling music]</i>

03:51.143 --> 03:54.408
<i>♪</i>

03:54.451 --> 03:57.062
Got the results
of your polygraph back.

03:57.106 --> 03:59.064
Whoo.

03:59.108 --> 04:00.327
You failed.

04:00.370 --> 04:02.285
Epically. 100%.

04:02.329 --> 04:03.982
I did?

04:04.026 --> 04:05.767
You may as well confess,

04:05.810 --> 04:08.900
make everything easier
on yourself.

04:08.944 --> 04:11.251
I don't even know
why I'm here.

04:11.294 --> 04:13.949
[chuckles] Well, I guess
this is gonna take a while.

04:13.992 --> 04:20.956
<i>♪</i>

04:34.361 --> 04:35.492
All right, Russ.

04:35.536 --> 04:37.625
Let's go over this
one more time.

04:37.668 --> 04:40.802
<i>narrator: Can a lie</i> <i>
be detected by a machine</i>

04:40.845 --> 04:44.458
<i>or squeezed out</i> <i>
under pressure?</i>

04:44.501 --> 04:47.199
It's been 24 hours.
You have to let him go.

04:47.243 --> 04:50.812
And get us something we can use
to bring him back for good.

04:50.855 --> 04:55.033
<i>narrator: Can a lie sneak into</i> <i>
our lives like a Trojan horse</i>

04:55.077 --> 04:58.123
<i>without us</i> <i>
even knowing it's there?</i>

04:58.167 --> 05:00.648
<i>Or is a lie more like a virus</i>

05:00.691 --> 05:04.739
<i>spread through the air</i> <i>
from one person to the next?</i>

05:04.782 --> 05:07.959
So I was at Betsy's mom's
and Russ wasn't around.

05:08.003 --> 05:10.919
So they must still
be holding him.

05:10.962 --> 05:13.487
You know what that means.

05:13.530 --> 05:16.620
We're looking closely at him.

05:16.664 --> 05:18.883
You really think he did it.

05:18.927 --> 05:22.191
<i>♪</i>

05:22.234 --> 05:26.848
The DA told my mom
everything points to Russ.

05:26.891 --> 05:30.242
Mm-hmm.
How 'bout that 911 call?

05:30.286 --> 05:31.548
Crying like a baby.

05:31.592 --> 05:33.376
I mean,
I could act better than that

05:33.420 --> 05:36.292
and I'm only
second semester theater.

05:37.075 --> 05:39.991
[sighs]
Listen, Janet. I apologize.

05:40.035 --> 05:42.385
We don't have enough
to charge him yet,

05:42.429 --> 05:44.996
<i>but the detectives are close.</i>

05:45.040 --> 05:48.565
You get him, Ms. Askey.

05:48.609 --> 05:50.654
I'm not sure what you mean

05:50.698 --> 05:53.048
you don't have enough
to charge him.

05:53.091 --> 05:54.484
<i>Uh...</i>

05:54.528 --> 05:57.574
I need probable cause
for the judge.

05:57.618 --> 06:02.231
So like, a witness, evidence,
stuff like that?

06:02.274 --> 06:03.537
<i>Yeah, stuff like that.</i>

06:03.580 --> 06:05.756
Uh, listen, Janet,
you will be the first person

06:05.800 --> 06:07.410
to find out
when we make the arrest.

06:07.454 --> 06:09.369
And again, I am so sorry, okay?

06:09.412 --> 06:10.848
<i>Bye now.</i>

06:13.068 --> 06:15.375
Sorry, but she's wrong.

06:15.418 --> 06:18.116
Why would the police lie?

06:19.248 --> 06:21.555
He's out now though, right?

06:21.598 --> 06:22.860
Whoa. Whoa, whoa.

06:22.904 --> 06:24.471
- Oh, I am--
- I mean--

06:24.514 --> 06:27.256
I'm sorry, sweetheart.

06:27.299 --> 06:29.389
You can't see Russ anymore.

06:29.432 --> 06:32.087
That's not a good idea.

06:34.306 --> 06:37.440
I can't see my dad?

06:37.484 --> 06:39.964
And I'll never see
my mom again.

06:40.008 --> 06:44.621
So what, you're just gonna
make me like--like an orphan?

06:44.665 --> 06:47.276
Well, he's not your real dad.

06:47.319 --> 06:50.235
<i>[soft emotional music]</i>

06:50.279 --> 06:51.715
<i>♪</i>

06:51.759 --> 06:54.457
He's the only dad
I ever knew.

06:54.501 --> 06:56.938
Well, you got
your grandmother.

06:56.981 --> 07:01.943
<i>♪</i>

07:01.986 --> 07:05.337
She was tired.

07:05.381 --> 07:06.556
You just let her leave.

07:06.600 --> 07:10.081
She should have stayed with us.

07:10.125 --> 07:12.780
I know sweetie.

07:12.823 --> 07:18.263
- I--
- I didn't get my hug.

07:18.307 --> 07:22.616
<i>♪</i>

07:22.659 --> 07:25.575
<i>narrator: Can a lie</i> <i>
be folded into a hug...</i>

07:25.619 --> 07:28.535
<i>[uneasy music]</i>

07:28.578 --> 07:31.842
<i>♪</i>

07:31.886 --> 07:36.586
<i>even from the ones you trust?</i>

07:36.630 --> 07:39.720
<i>[phone rings]</i>

07:39.763 --> 07:41.765
- Hello?
- Hey.

07:41.809 --> 07:45.029
Um, a detective called

07:45.073 --> 07:47.205
and he wants to come by
and talk to me.

07:47.249 --> 07:49.469
- When?
- Couple days.

07:49.512 --> 07:51.775
Could you make it any sooner?

07:51.819 --> 07:54.256
Well, we have that
big mold inspection tomorrow.

07:54.299 --> 07:56.084
We'll reschedule it, Mark.

07:56.127 --> 07:58.695
Pretty sure the police
need our help.

07:58.739 --> 08:01.742
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

08:01.785 --> 08:07.225
<i>♪</i>

08:10.359 --> 08:11.621
<i>narrator: Back in 2007,</i>

08:11.665 --> 08:14.450
<i>Betsy's light shined on Pam.</i>

08:14.494 --> 08:17.409
<i>They were friends,</i> <i>
good friends.</i>

08:17.453 --> 08:21.805
<i>Pam even asked Betsy</i> <i>
to DJ her daughter's wedding.</i>

08:21.849 --> 08:23.764
Hey, Travis!

08:23.807 --> 08:25.200
Travis!

08:25.243 --> 08:28.464
Come "Hokey Pokey"
with your mom!

08:28.508 --> 08:30.945
Boo!

08:30.988 --> 08:33.295
<i>["Hokey Pokey" playing]</i>

08:33.338 --> 08:35.602
Can we get
the bride up in here?

08:35.645 --> 08:37.734
[cheers and applause]

08:37.778 --> 08:40.084
- Yay!
- Yeah, Sarah!

08:40.128 --> 08:42.130
Everybody, backside!

08:42.173 --> 08:46.221
<i>narrator: Pam took pride in</i> <i>
making all the right moves.</i>

08:46.264 --> 08:49.659
<i>A purposeful choreography</i> <i>
through life.</i>

08:49.703 --> 08:51.313
Look at that mama
of the bride!

08:51.356 --> 08:53.794
Who knew she could
get down like this?

08:53.837 --> 08:55.186
Well, Sarah didn't.

08:55.230 --> 08:56.492
She didn't want me
to pay you, Bets.

08:56.536 --> 08:58.059
She said we could
just use an iPod.

08:58.102 --> 09:00.017
Mom!

09:00.061 --> 09:02.367
Well, happy to give you
the friend rate.

09:02.411 --> 09:04.065
No, no, no. You get full pay.

09:04.108 --> 09:07.459
I was telling her,
Bets needs the work.

09:07.503 --> 09:09.244
Pam, why don't you just
go ahead and give me the mic.

09:09.287 --> 09:10.637
I'm so sorry, Betsy.

09:10.680 --> 09:11.725
For what?

09:11.768 --> 09:13.596
I'm paying
for this whole shebang.

09:13.640 --> 09:17.208
<i>♪</i>

09:17.252 --> 09:18.688
Hey, you know what?

09:18.732 --> 09:20.995
I'm so happy to be here.

09:21.038 --> 09:22.910
We're having a good time.

09:22.953 --> 09:26.566
This--this gig's on me.

09:26.609 --> 09:30.134
No. Really?
No charge?

09:30.178 --> 09:31.658
- No charge.
- [gasps]

09:31.701 --> 09:33.616
Congratulations, Sarah.

09:33.660 --> 09:35.879
<i>♪</i>

09:35.923 --> 09:38.055
Okay, everybody. Here we go.

09:38.099 --> 09:39.970
Put your whole self in.

09:40.014 --> 09:42.712
<i>♪ Put your whole self in,</i> <i>
put your whole self out ♪</i>

09:42.756 --> 09:43.844
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
They say when someone</i>

09:43.887 --> 09:45.846
<i>shows you who they are,</i>

09:45.889 --> 09:48.196
<i>believe it.</i>

09:48.239 --> 09:50.981
<i>But would Lincoln County</i> <i>
detectives see Pam</i>

09:51.025 --> 09:52.417
<i>and believe her?</i>

09:52.461 --> 09:54.289
You boys want a cookie?

09:54.332 --> 09:56.247
I'm baking up a storm
for the holidays.

09:56.291 --> 09:57.901
- I don't mind if I do.
- Oh.

09:57.945 --> 10:00.512
No need to take up
any of your time, Mrs. Hupp.

10:00.556 --> 10:03.124
We only need to talk
to your husband.

10:03.167 --> 10:05.605
Sure. No problem.

10:11.654 --> 10:14.439
Okay, so, Mr. Hupp,
on the night of the 27th,

10:14.483 --> 10:17.094
you were at home?
- Yes.

10:19.749 --> 10:23.187
Oh, you play ball?

10:23.231 --> 10:24.841
AAA down in Florida.

10:24.885 --> 10:26.060
Oh.

10:26.103 --> 10:28.802
- Till he threw out his arm.
- Mm.

10:28.845 --> 10:30.412
[crunching loudly]

10:32.632 --> 10:34.024
Um...

10:34.068 --> 10:38.463
hon, why don't you play that
voicemail Betsy left ya?

10:40.683 --> 10:42.293
[phone beeps]

10:42.337 --> 10:45.296
<i>Happy Christmas, Mark.</i> <i>
Hope you're good.</i>

10:45.340 --> 10:49.039
<i>Thanks for loaning me Pam.</i>

10:49.083 --> 10:51.912
So full of life.

10:51.955 --> 10:55.002
That was 7:00? Mm.

10:55.045 --> 10:58.527
Yep, 7:04.
- Mm, mm.

10:58.570 --> 11:00.311
So I take it
you knew Betsy then.

11:00.355 --> 11:02.313
Through Pam.

11:02.357 --> 11:03.706
Didn't know Russ though.

11:03.750 --> 11:06.274
Who did, honestly?

11:06.317 --> 11:08.319
I've been through how many
of their separations

11:08.363 --> 11:12.280
and I'm still on the tip
of the iceberg over here.

11:12.323 --> 11:16.414
And just some of the stuff
she'd say.

11:19.113 --> 11:21.768
Did you guys
ever find that letter

11:21.811 --> 11:25.380
that Betsy was writing?

11:26.294 --> 11:28.688
- No.
- Oh.

11:28.731 --> 11:30.080
Some of the officers
the other day

11:30.124 --> 11:32.256
seemed really interested.

11:32.300 --> 11:34.650
Kept asking me.

11:34.694 --> 11:38.698
Um, it was just some letter
or something

11:38.741 --> 11:41.135
that Bets was gonna email
to tell me about

11:41.178 --> 11:43.485
something Russ did to her.

11:43.528 --> 11:46.314
I don't know if she deleted it
or whatever.

11:46.357 --> 11:47.663
Why would she email it to you

11:47.707 --> 11:51.406
versus talking to you about it?

11:51.449 --> 11:54.496
Uh, I mean,

11:54.539 --> 11:56.324
Betsy emailed all the time.

11:56.367 --> 11:59.153
You know, she emailed people.

11:59.196 --> 12:01.895
She'd email about this and that
and just general stuff.

12:01.938 --> 12:04.506
You know, she loved email.

12:04.549 --> 12:09.032
Knowing Bets, uh, she probably
got charged to text,

12:09.076 --> 12:11.252
so that's why email.

12:11.295 --> 12:14.037
Save the money.

12:14.081 --> 12:15.865
- Got it.
- [chuckles]

12:15.909 --> 12:18.085
Do you know what was
in this email?

12:18.128 --> 12:20.870
Russ started
playing this game

12:20.914 --> 12:23.873
of putting a pillow
over her face.

12:23.917 --> 12:26.397
And he'd say this is
what it's gonna feel like

12:26.441 --> 12:30.924
when you die or whatever. Um,

12:30.967 --> 12:33.709
I didn't really know the guy,

12:33.753 --> 12:37.713
but just from what Bets said,

12:37.757 --> 12:40.803
he seemed sorta--

12:40.847 --> 12:43.197
- Abusive?
- Real abusive.

12:43.240 --> 12:44.198
Mm-hmm.
- Yeah.

12:44.241 --> 12:46.722
Yeah.

12:46.766 --> 12:48.332
And I was like,
well, email it to me.

12:48.376 --> 12:50.508
But I never got it.

12:50.552 --> 12:52.989
And would you be willing
to testify to all this?

12:53.033 --> 12:57.864
If you think it'd be helpful.

12:57.907 --> 12:59.387
[sighs]

12:59.430 --> 13:02.346
<i>[unsettling music]</i>

13:02.390 --> 13:04.044
<i>♪</i>

13:04.087 --> 13:05.045
[sniffs]

13:05.088 --> 13:07.656
<i>♪</i>

13:07.699 --> 13:11.138
Tina, call the judge!

13:11.181 --> 13:13.488
We have our probable cause.

13:16.273 --> 13:17.884
So you given
any more thought

13:17.927 --> 13:19.886
to your cousin's offer?

13:19.929 --> 13:21.844
Joel, that's the lawyer,

13:21.888 --> 13:24.412
he said that
you would be the one

13:24.455 --> 13:26.501
to have to contact him first.

13:26.544 --> 13:27.894
I don't know.

13:27.937 --> 13:29.765
Feels like
getting a lawyer means

13:29.809 --> 13:31.767
that I'm somebody
who needs a lawyer, you know?

13:31.811 --> 13:35.640
- I just--
- I just want to get past this.

13:35.684 --> 13:37.294
Mom, come on.
You can do that later.

13:37.338 --> 13:39.209
Otherwise, it'll stick.

13:39.253 --> 13:40.558
Are you gonna do these dishes?

13:40.602 --> 13:42.430
Sorry, what?
Didn't get that.

13:42.473 --> 13:43.866
[chuckles]

13:43.910 --> 13:45.259
[door slams open]
- Sheriff's Department!

13:45.302 --> 13:46.782
[screams]

13:47.652 --> 13:49.089
[breathing heavily]

13:49.132 --> 13:51.178
[door slams open]

13:51.221 --> 13:52.396
Russell Faria,
you're under arrest

13:52.440 --> 13:54.572
for the murder of Betsy Faria.

13:54.616 --> 13:56.444
- It's okay.
- No!

13:56.487 --> 13:59.055
Ah--
[handcuffs clicking]

13:59.099 --> 14:00.100
- Get up.
- [grunts]

14:00.143 --> 14:01.884
[silverware clattering]

14:01.928 --> 14:03.886
Russ, it's okay!

14:03.930 --> 14:06.846
<i>[sinister music]</i>

14:06.889 --> 14:09.544
<i>♪</i>

14:09.587 --> 14:14.114
[siren wailing]

14:14.157 --> 14:17.160
<i>♪</i>

14:17.204 --> 14:18.814
I want a lawyer.

14:18.858 --> 14:20.860
<i>♪</i>

14:24.298 --> 14:26.735
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
He rolled in from the city,</i>

14:26.778 --> 14:29.433
<i>a busy man from</i> <i>
a high-rise firm in St. Louis.</i>

14:29.477 --> 14:32.915
<i>Russ' new lawyer,</i> <i>
Joel Schwartz</i>

14:32.959 --> 14:35.526
<i>was about to encounter--</i>

14:35.570 --> 14:38.616
<i>well, he had no idea.</i>

14:38.660 --> 14:40.792
Green Gables?

14:40.836 --> 14:42.185
It's not even green.

14:42.229 --> 14:46.276
Wait, it's not?
I Yelped and--

14:46.320 --> 14:50.150
and this definitely looked
like the best hotel in town.

14:50.193 --> 14:54.632
Um, but there is a--
a Holiday Inn down the 47.

14:54.676 --> 14:57.766
Do you want me to check that?
- What color are their gables?

14:57.809 --> 15:00.073
I can check.

15:00.116 --> 15:01.813
- [chuckles]
- Oh, you're kidding.

15:01.857 --> 15:03.250
- Yeah, I'm kidding.
- Oh, right.

15:03.293 --> 15:04.512
It's our first day
working together.

15:04.555 --> 15:05.774
You get a pass.

15:05.817 --> 15:07.428
Hey, I just got
a probable cause statement

15:07.471 --> 15:10.126
from the Lincoln County
Sheriff's office.

15:10.170 --> 15:11.780
Looks like an eight-year-old
wrote it.

15:11.823 --> 15:14.130
There's gotta be a more
substantial report coming.

15:14.174 --> 15:16.828
Should we wait before
we sit down with Russell then?

15:16.872 --> 15:18.961
No. No.
We've got a guy with a temper,

15:19.005 --> 15:20.267
volatile relationship,

15:20.310 --> 15:22.312
marriage breaking up,
getting back together.

15:22.356 --> 15:25.576
And strangers don't stab
their victims 50 plus times.

15:25.620 --> 15:28.318
So, uh, I take it
you've represented

15:28.362 --> 15:31.321
a lot of guys
like Russ then before.

15:31.365 --> 15:32.627
Oh, yeah.

15:32.670 --> 15:35.586
Oh, yeah, it's kinda my jam.
- Yeah, mine too.

15:35.630 --> 15:37.588
Um, you know, I think so.

15:37.632 --> 15:41.549
Because this is
my first murder trial.

15:41.592 --> 15:44.421
In my experience,
the stats aren't wrong.

15:44.465 --> 15:46.075
We got the husband
of the victim here.

15:46.119 --> 15:48.077
- Right.
- Right?

15:48.121 --> 15:52.690
<i>♪</i>

15:52.734 --> 15:54.388
[sighs]

15:54.431 --> 15:57.608
<i>♪</i>

15:57.652 --> 15:59.001
Hey, Pam, you heard?

15:59.045 --> 16:01.351
Betsy Faria's husband
got arrested.

16:01.395 --> 16:02.657
No way.

16:02.700 --> 16:04.964
Mm-hmm. News just said so.

16:05.007 --> 16:06.182
He goes to my sister's church.

16:06.226 --> 16:08.358
Can you believe that?

16:08.402 --> 16:10.012
I guess you never know
what's going on

16:10.056 --> 16:11.535
inside other people's houses.

16:11.579 --> 16:14.408
<i>♪</i>

16:14.451 --> 16:15.626
[slurps]

16:20.240 --> 16:21.981
We're here to see Russ Faria.

16:22.024 --> 16:24.287
He's in holding.
You can wait over there.

16:25.941 --> 16:27.595
Hey, excuse me.

16:28.857 --> 16:30.163
You can't go in there.

16:30.206 --> 16:31.164
Why are you talking
to my client

16:31.207 --> 16:33.340
after he asked for a lawyer?

16:33.383 --> 16:34.689
Huh?

16:38.432 --> 16:41.130
That's him.
That's Joel Schwartz.

16:41.174 --> 16:43.002
I like his style.

16:43.045 --> 16:45.352
He looks like Tom Hanks
from "Splash."

16:45.395 --> 16:46.744
How much do you think
that haircut cost?

16:46.788 --> 16:49.573
He already put in
a request for evidence.

16:49.617 --> 16:51.401
He's good.

16:51.445 --> 16:55.231
We don't let guys like that
dick us around, Tina.

16:57.233 --> 16:59.322
Thanks for coming.

17:01.107 --> 17:03.674
Yeah, well, we're here
to help you, Russ.

17:03.718 --> 17:05.763
First off, is it true
that you talked to the police

17:05.807 --> 17:07.896
for 24 hours straight?

17:07.939 --> 17:10.725
Yeah.

17:10.768 --> 17:13.075
How much did you tell them?

17:13.119 --> 17:16.035
All of it.

17:16.078 --> 17:17.949
All of what?

17:17.993 --> 17:19.342
The truth.

17:25.348 --> 17:29.613
Am I really going to have
to go in front of a jury

17:29.657 --> 17:31.615
because you two
can't get a confession

17:31.659 --> 17:33.095
out of this maniac?

17:33.139 --> 17:34.444
The guy's a good liar.

17:34.488 --> 17:36.359
He's sticking to his Arby's
and game night.

17:36.403 --> 17:38.318
I wish to God
I hadn't gone to game night,

17:38.361 --> 17:40.146
but that's where I was,

17:40.189 --> 17:42.191
so how can everybody
think I did this?

17:42.235 --> 17:43.627
It doesn't matter
what everyone thinks.

17:43.671 --> 17:46.804
It matters what
the prosecution can prove.

17:46.848 --> 17:49.285
Wait.

17:49.329 --> 17:52.288
Do you think I killed Betsy?

17:52.332 --> 17:54.116
I don't know
what I think yet, Russ.

17:54.160 --> 17:55.335
Okay.

17:55.378 --> 17:59.121
But...don't you
have to believe me?

17:59.165 --> 18:01.515
Isn't that, like, part of this?

18:01.558 --> 18:05.432
I'm bumping on
the same thing you are.

18:05.475 --> 18:06.824
I'm not even sure
why we're sitting here

18:06.868 --> 18:08.783
if your alibi checks out.

18:08.826 --> 18:10.611
Talk to my friends then.

18:13.831 --> 18:15.920
<i>That alibi's still</i> <i>
tough to get around.</i>

18:15.964 --> 18:19.010
We could widen the net,
look at a few more suspects.

18:19.054 --> 18:20.447
You're the detective,

18:20.490 --> 18:21.926
but just because
a pocket square

18:21.970 --> 18:25.234
rolls in from the city
doesn't mean that we're wrong.

18:25.278 --> 18:26.496
So what do we have?

18:26.540 --> 18:27.758
There must've been a cleanup.

18:27.802 --> 18:30.021
There wasn't blood
on Russ' clothing?

18:30.065 --> 18:31.588
Not a drop.

18:32.633 --> 18:34.548
Do we have
the luminol photos back?

18:34.591 --> 18:39.248
Those would show
if there was blood cleaned up.

18:39.292 --> 18:40.815
Camera malfunctioned.

18:40.858 --> 18:42.121
Photos showed nothing.

18:42.164 --> 18:44.035
Totally blank.

18:44.079 --> 18:47.126
Should we take a look
just to be sure?

18:47.169 --> 18:48.518
If he says they're blank,
they're blank.

18:48.562 --> 18:49.389
What's the point?

18:49.432 --> 18:52.305
Get over here, McCarrick!

18:52.348 --> 18:54.524
This guy stabbed
his wife 57 times

18:54.568 --> 18:56.526
and he didn't do it stark naked

18:56.570 --> 18:58.485
spraying Lysol out of his ass,

18:58.528 --> 19:01.183
so he must've missed a spot.

19:01.227 --> 19:04.186
If you were at game night,

19:04.230 --> 19:06.188
then who took Betsy home?

19:06.232 --> 19:07.711
Her friend, Pam.

19:07.755 --> 19:08.973
Pam.

19:09.017 --> 19:11.541
Why don't you
tell me about Pam?

19:11.585 --> 19:13.152
She's--

19:13.195 --> 19:14.588
I don't know.

19:14.631 --> 19:16.590
Nice lady.

19:16.633 --> 19:18.809
"Nice lady."

19:18.853 --> 19:23.074
Okay, and what about
your stepdaughter, Lily?

19:23.118 --> 19:24.119
She got an ex-boyfriend?

19:24.163 --> 19:27.122
Oh, he's a huge tool,

19:27.166 --> 19:29.733
but I don't think
he could've done this.

19:29.777 --> 19:31.213
Well, we should
still check him out

19:31.257 --> 19:34.216
just to dot the Ts
and cross the--

19:37.132 --> 19:38.438
Okay, Russ.

19:38.481 --> 19:40.831
Well, that should be
enough for us to start.

19:40.875 --> 19:44.226
Whoa.
What happens now?

19:44.270 --> 19:46.228
Well, you'll be held
until trial.

19:46.272 --> 19:49.927
You mean in jail?

19:49.971 --> 19:52.930
<i>[soft music]</i>

19:52.974 --> 19:54.671
<i>♪</i>

19:54.715 --> 19:57.761
Nate and I are gonna
sort this out, okay?

19:57.805 --> 20:00.242
In the meantime, you do not
talk to the police without me,

20:00.286 --> 20:02.592
you understand?

20:02.636 --> 20:09.556
<i>♪</i>

20:12.385 --> 20:13.603
<i>Why would he ask us</i>

20:13.647 --> 20:15.475
to interview
five independent witnesses?

20:15.518 --> 20:17.955
That's just gonna
make him look bad.

20:17.999 --> 20:19.130
[sighs]

20:19.174 --> 20:20.480
I'm sorry.

20:20.523 --> 20:22.264
I'm still trying to pick up
on your social cues.

20:22.308 --> 20:23.613
What's the sign?

20:23.657 --> 20:25.093
I've represented
a lot of guilty people,

20:25.136 --> 20:27.443
but it's the innocent ones
that keep me up at night.

20:27.487 --> 20:29.793
Wait, you think
that he didn't do this?

20:29.837 --> 20:33.449
<i>♪</i>

20:33.493 --> 20:36.235
I guess
the pressure's on now.

20:36.278 --> 20:38.672
<i>♪</i>

20:38.715 --> 20:41.196
If the clothes he was wearing
don't have blood on them,

20:41.240 --> 20:44.243
then he must've changed,
washed up.

20:44.286 --> 20:45.635
Was there blood
in the bathroom?

20:45.679 --> 20:47.768
Did you take apart the shower?

20:47.811 --> 20:49.378
Morning, Leah.

20:49.422 --> 20:51.467
You guys are just sitting
around sucking on your thumbs

20:51.511 --> 20:53.513
and you have no confession,
which means you've just laid

20:53.556 --> 20:56.429
ten times
the amount of work at my feet.

20:56.472 --> 20:59.127
You were just elected DA,
what, a month ago?

20:59.170 --> 21:01.608
It shows.

21:01.651 --> 21:03.087
I thought you were excited
about the big case.

21:03.131 --> 21:04.828
Well, not if I'm gonna lose.

21:04.872 --> 21:06.830
I have to show people
why they elected me.

21:06.874 --> 21:10.181
Maybe someone could do
a test drive from Arby's.

21:10.225 --> 21:12.009
I saw the receipt.
It's timestamped.

21:12.053 --> 21:15.491
Thank you, Tina,
who is not a detective.

21:15.535 --> 21:17.928
How could we ever show
that it was possible

21:17.972 --> 21:21.323
for Russ to get home from
Arby's in time to kill Betsy?

21:21.367 --> 21:23.064
He must've gone
over the speed limit.

21:23.107 --> 21:24.370
I'll take care of it.

21:24.413 --> 21:27.416
Now, you two, please
take apart the house

21:27.460 --> 21:29.462
and find me the blood.

21:29.505 --> 21:32.203
<i>[upbeat rock music]</i>

21:32.247 --> 21:33.509
<i>11:41 a.m.</i>

21:33.553 --> 21:35.511
Detective Brian McCarrick here.

21:35.555 --> 21:37.905
Leaving Arby's
en route to 130 Sumac Drive.

21:37.948 --> 21:39.733
[tires squealing]

21:39.776 --> 21:46.696
<i>♪</i>

21:59.100 --> 22:02.538
[tires squealing]

22:05.106 --> 22:06.281
Boom!

22:06.325 --> 22:07.543
Plenty of time to kill you.

22:07.587 --> 22:09.197
[chuckles]
Yah!

22:09.240 --> 22:11.242
<i>♪</i>

22:11.286 --> 22:13.549
<i>What the friggin' hell?</i>

22:14.420 --> 22:17.205
[sniffs]
Ugh!

22:17.248 --> 22:20.164
The entire floor
stinks like that?

22:20.208 --> 22:23.646
- Mold. It's bad.
- Ugh.

22:23.690 --> 22:26.997
We might have to dip into
the Florida money.

22:27.041 --> 22:28.608
It's gone.

22:30.784 --> 22:32.046
All of it?

22:32.089 --> 22:33.874
How'd you think
I paid for that flip house

22:33.917 --> 22:35.136
when we're behind the mortgage
here?

22:35.179 --> 22:36.398
- - Well, I--
- I don't know.

22:36.442 --> 22:38.879
Maybe your disability money.

22:38.922 --> 22:42.361
I told you about that
stupid letter I got, Mark.

22:42.404 --> 22:44.450
They said I don't
qualify anymore.

22:45.625 --> 22:48.976
But your bad leg.

22:49.019 --> 22:51.239
Tell it to the man.

22:51.282 --> 22:52.632
<i>[unsettling music]</i>

22:52.675 --> 22:56.940
[garbage disposal rumbling]

22:56.984 --> 22:59.900
I'll get us the money.

22:59.943 --> 23:06.863
<i>♪</i>

23:10.911 --> 23:12.303
Hey.

23:12.347 --> 23:14.436
I just got back from seeing
all those gamer guys.

23:14.480 --> 23:16.351
Super sweet group of dudes.

23:16.395 --> 23:19.310
I've got five people

23:19.354 --> 23:21.835
who said that
Russ left at 9:00.

23:21.878 --> 23:23.619
Well, you can't be
at game night and the Arby's

23:23.663 --> 23:26.796
at the same time
you're killing your wife.

23:26.840 --> 23:28.755
So I was looking
at these autopsy--

23:28.798 --> 23:30.147
do you mind if I show this to
you while you're eating lunch?

23:30.191 --> 23:31.192
- No.
- Okay.

23:31.235 --> 23:33.934
It looks like there is a bruise

23:33.977 --> 23:36.153
on Betsy's neck here.
- Mm.

23:36.197 --> 23:37.546
And then it looks like
the knife

23:37.590 --> 23:40.027
was stuck into that same spot

23:40.070 --> 23:42.072
after she was dead.

23:42.116 --> 23:44.858
Maybe the bruise means
she was strangled first?

23:44.901 --> 23:47.904
And then put the knife there
to cover up the fingerprints.

23:47.948 --> 23:50.516
Yeah, it's weird.

23:50.559 --> 23:52.996
She has so many stab wounds
on her back, Joel,

23:53.040 --> 23:55.477
but there's no blood
on the carpet.

23:55.521 --> 23:56.739
And they're all the same size,

23:56.783 --> 23:59.394
same depth,
all made post-mortem.

23:59.438 --> 24:00.961
Methodical, not passionate,

24:01.004 --> 24:02.528
but trying to make it
look like that.

24:02.571 --> 24:05.052
Is that the number one
criminal defense attorney

24:05.095 --> 24:06.488
in all of St. Louis?

24:06.532 --> 24:08.098
[chuckles]
Number two, actually.

24:08.142 --> 24:10.013
- That's right. Number two.
- Yeah.

24:10.057 --> 24:11.406
And you must be,

24:11.450 --> 24:13.190
let me guess,
our district attorney.

24:13.234 --> 24:14.409
You can call me Leah.

24:14.453 --> 24:15.845
- Leah. Oh, Leah--
- Yes.

24:15.889 --> 24:18.369
We still haven't received
our luminol photos

24:18.413 --> 24:20.067
from the crime scene.

24:20.110 --> 24:22.809
Photos didn't come out.
There was a camera malfunction.

24:22.852 --> 24:25.028
- Oh, well, that's too bad.
- Yeah.

24:25.072 --> 24:26.334
We're still gonna need
to see those.

24:26.377 --> 24:28.945
And the polygraph
results too.

24:28.989 --> 24:31.208
Photos and polygraph
coming right up.

24:31.252 --> 24:32.819
Okay.

24:32.862 --> 24:35.822
Hey, Danny, this one's on me.

24:35.865 --> 24:38.389
They're guests in our town.

24:38.433 --> 24:39.521
Night, boys.

24:39.565 --> 24:41.958
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

24:43.307 --> 24:44.700
Uh...
- Oh, boy.

24:44.744 --> 24:47.224
Okay, okay. What's next?

24:47.268 --> 24:48.878
- Let's go to motive to kill.
- All right.

24:48.922 --> 24:52.055
So based on
the detectives' interviews,

24:52.099 --> 24:53.535
it seems like
they're gonna go with the fact

24:53.579 --> 24:55.624
that Russ was this rage monster
who snapped--

24:55.668 --> 24:57.844
Askey will go with
that, sure, but if she's smart,

24:57.887 --> 24:59.541
she'll pile on
a bunch of other reasons.

24:59.585 --> 25:01.021
Or it could be insurance.

25:01.064 --> 25:02.457
Do you want me to check to see
if Betsy had a policy?

25:02.501 --> 25:04.198
She was terminally ill.

25:04.241 --> 25:05.547
I mean, if he was gonna
kill her for the money,

25:05.591 --> 25:08.898
why wouldn't he just wait
a couple of months?

25:08.942 --> 25:15.122
What about SODDIs?
"Some other dude did it."

25:15.165 --> 25:16.427
- Oh.
- Yeah.

25:16.471 --> 25:17.907
[chuckles]

25:17.951 --> 25:19.996
I just went through 500 pages

25:20.040 --> 25:23.434
of the daughter's boyfriend's
text messages.

25:23.478 --> 25:25.045
- And?
- I wouldn't date the guy,

25:25.088 --> 25:27.569
but he didn't kill Betsy.

25:27.613 --> 25:30.224
What about that Pam lady?

25:30.267 --> 25:32.748
I mean, she was the last one
to see Betsy alive.

25:32.792 --> 25:34.271
We definitely need
to see her cell records.

25:34.315 --> 25:35.751
I have tried.

25:35.795 --> 25:38.275
But the DA doesn't seem
to think that we need them.

25:38.319 --> 25:40.147
Yeah, well, that's because
Pam doesn't fit into

25:40.190 --> 25:41.975
what Askey wants to see.

25:42.018 --> 25:43.454
- That's a good point.
- Right?

25:43.498 --> 25:46.414
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:46.457 --> 25:48.024
<i>♪</i>

25:48.068 --> 25:49.591
[sighs]

25:49.635 --> 25:51.158
<i>♪</i>

25:51.201 --> 25:52.768
I have to go home
and tuck in the kids

25:52.812 --> 25:55.597
or Chris will get his panties
in a twist.

25:55.641 --> 25:57.381
Yeah, we wouldn't want that,
would we?

25:57.425 --> 26:00.602
Mm-mm.

26:00.646 --> 26:02.604
Well, let's see.

26:02.648 --> 26:05.738
There's the bloody smear
on the light switch.

26:05.781 --> 26:07.827
- Test that against Russ.
- Okay.

26:07.870 --> 26:11.787
And then there's
the bloody slippers.

26:11.831 --> 26:13.876
That is a wrinkle.

26:13.920 --> 26:16.183
Why would he put his slippers
back in the closet

26:16.226 --> 26:17.880
after he killed her?

26:17.924 --> 26:19.621
And weird that there's blood
on the slippers,

26:19.665 --> 26:22.015
but not on his clothes.

26:24.452 --> 26:27.760
Maybe he did kill her naked.

26:28.935 --> 26:31.590
So test that against Russ.
Anyone else?

26:31.633 --> 26:34.941
Why?

26:34.984 --> 26:37.204
It's my first
major murder case.

26:37.247 --> 26:39.510
I--
[inhales deeply]

26:39.554 --> 26:42.557
it's a lot.

26:50.391 --> 26:52.219
All right.
- [clears throat]

26:52.262 --> 26:55.396
Well, if you're leaving,

26:55.439 --> 26:58.094
you should probably
take a look at that first.

26:58.138 --> 27:01.054
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:01.097 --> 27:05.493
<i>♪</i>

27:05.536 --> 27:08.365
<i>narrator: Pam was always</i> <i>
working on something</i>

27:08.409 --> 27:11.412
<i>as she worked her way</i> <i>
to the top.</i>

27:11.455 --> 27:15.634
[phone ringing]

27:17.157 --> 27:19.028
Hello?

27:19.072 --> 27:20.987
Yeah, that's me.

27:23.206 --> 27:26.688
Yeah, I could do that.

27:26.732 --> 27:29.125
See you then.

27:29.169 --> 27:31.084
Mm-hmm.

27:33.956 --> 27:36.872
The DA wants to talk to me.

27:36.916 --> 27:38.526
Again?

27:38.569 --> 27:40.920
No, Travis, try and keep up.

27:40.963 --> 27:43.966
That was the cops
I talked to last time.

27:44.010 --> 27:45.576
[grunts]

27:45.620 --> 27:47.361
This is the DA.

27:47.404 --> 27:50.451
<i>narrator: Just now,</i> <i>
she had a story to tell</i>

27:50.494 --> 27:54.673
<i>and just the right person</i> <i>
to tell it to.</i>

27:57.719 --> 28:00.591
[indistinct chatter]

28:04.900 --> 28:06.772
Joel.

28:06.815 --> 28:08.121
I like your pocket square.

28:08.164 --> 28:09.731
There's not many men
that can pull off

28:09.775 --> 28:12.299
a pink pocket square.

28:12.342 --> 28:14.649
We're here
for Pam Hupp's cell data.

28:14.693 --> 28:16.172
Yeah.

28:16.216 --> 28:18.871
You can go ahead
and analyze the phone anytime.

28:18.914 --> 28:20.873
No, not the phone itself.

28:20.916 --> 28:23.353
The raw data is converted
into a readable map

28:23.397 --> 28:25.965
for both sides.
- Okay.

28:26.008 --> 28:27.053
Go for it.

28:27.096 --> 28:28.315
The state's analysis center

28:28.358 --> 28:29.316
is the one that makes the map.

28:29.359 --> 28:30.578
And you and I both know

28:30.621 --> 28:32.754
that we don't have access
to those services.

28:32.798 --> 28:35.191
Only you can make that request
to the Sheriff's office.

28:35.235 --> 28:36.410
So how do you suggest

28:36.453 --> 28:39.761
we convert raw cell data
on our own?

28:39.805 --> 28:41.110
I don't know, Joel.

28:41.154 --> 28:43.896
Google it?

28:43.939 --> 28:45.071
- Nah.
- No.

28:45.114 --> 28:46.986
No, you'll send me
the cell map

28:47.029 --> 28:49.205
and the luminol photos.
- Which I have been requesting.

28:49.249 --> 28:51.207
And the physical evidence and
everything else that you have

28:51.251 --> 28:52.905
because that is how this works.

28:52.948 --> 28:54.776
Right, you old pro.

28:54.820 --> 28:57.126
I'm gonna have Tina
put together a disc for you.

28:57.170 --> 28:58.954
A really nice disc.

28:58.998 --> 29:00.173
Look forward to that.

29:00.216 --> 29:02.088
That was easy.

29:02.131 --> 29:03.698
Thanks for coming
all the way down!

29:05.091 --> 29:07.093
What a baby.

29:07.136 --> 29:10.052
<i>[soft emotional music]</i>

29:10.096 --> 29:17.233
<i>♪</i>

29:22.935 --> 29:24.632
Mom would have hated this.

29:24.675 --> 29:26.765
They really tore
the place apart.

29:26.808 --> 29:30.159
<i>♪</i>

29:30.203 --> 29:33.206
- - Um, I'm--
- I'm just gonna get my new kitten

29:33.249 --> 29:37.993
and then we can
just get out of here.

29:38.037 --> 29:45.174
<i>♪</i>

30:03.497 --> 30:05.673
How can you even look at him?

30:05.716 --> 30:07.153
Just because
you don't like him--

30:07.196 --> 30:08.502
He called me the C-word.

30:08.545 --> 30:10.069
'Cause you stole money
from Grandma.

30:10.112 --> 30:11.853
Shut up.

30:11.897 --> 30:15.683
- Whatever. Let's just go.
- Come on.

30:17.598 --> 30:19.905
Mom always left those on.

30:19.948 --> 30:26.868
<i>♪</i>

30:34.136 --> 30:36.704
Wait.

30:36.747 --> 30:38.358
It looks like Pam
took two showers.

30:38.401 --> 30:40.534
One the night Betsy died,

30:40.577 --> 30:41.883
and one the next morning.

30:41.927 --> 30:43.319
What the hell?

30:43.363 --> 30:45.713
This latest cell phone info
from the prosecution,

30:45.756 --> 30:47.106
it's useless.

30:47.149 --> 30:49.412
This is thousands of pages,

30:49.456 --> 30:51.719
thousands of pages of garbage.

30:53.634 --> 30:55.636
Nothing in this case is easy.

30:58.944 --> 31:01.511
<i>narrator: Here they were,</i> <i>
together at last.</i>

31:01.555 --> 31:03.513
[slurping] <i>
narrator: Pam and Leah Askey,</i>

31:03.557 --> 31:05.733
<i>just two public servants</i>

31:05.776 --> 31:08.431
<i>working for the common good.</i>

31:08.475 --> 31:10.564
- Hi.
- Hi.

31:10.607 --> 31:13.523
Sorry I am
such a sweaty Betty.

31:13.567 --> 31:15.525
I came straight from Zumba.

31:15.569 --> 31:17.484
You do Zumba?
I do Zumba.

31:17.527 --> 31:20.052
- Tuesday, Thursday.
- I'm Wednesday, Friday.

31:20.095 --> 31:21.618
[chuckles]

31:21.662 --> 31:23.969
It is so nice
to officially meet you.

31:24.012 --> 31:26.362
- Mm-hmm.
- Have a seat.

31:26.406 --> 31:31.759
You have been through so much.

31:33.369 --> 31:36.851
Joel, look at this.

31:36.895 --> 31:39.941
That's to do
with the life insurance.

31:39.985 --> 31:41.203
Oh, Russ,

31:41.247 --> 31:44.424
he was just getting
really creepy, you know?

31:44.467 --> 31:48.036
And--and he was making
her really nervous...

31:48.080 --> 31:49.081
Mm-hmm.

31:49.124 --> 31:50.560
- With the pillow.
- Mm-hmm.

31:50.604 --> 31:51.910
And, you know,
she'd turn around

31:51.953 --> 31:54.347
and he'd just be,
like, staring at her.

31:54.390 --> 31:55.652
Stuff like that.

31:55.696 --> 31:57.437
And four days
before he killed her...

31:57.480 --> 32:01.571
Betsy changed the beneficiary
from Russ to Pam.

32:03.486 --> 32:05.793
We got Pam's motive to kill.

32:05.836 --> 32:07.012
SODDI.

32:10.580 --> 32:12.974
This change of beneficiary
thing is really

32:13.018 --> 32:15.759
gonna help our case.
- Oh, my God.

32:15.803 --> 32:17.674
You think Russ found out
about it

32:17.718 --> 32:19.415
and that's what made him snap.

32:19.459 --> 32:20.634
Yep.

32:20.677 --> 32:21.852
Betsy took him off the policy

32:21.896 --> 32:23.767
and he killed her
in a fit of rage.

32:23.811 --> 32:26.727
- Well, that makes total sense.
- Unfortunately,

32:26.770 --> 32:29.469
Betsy's like a lot of
abused women I've seen,

32:29.512 --> 32:31.775
just trapped in a bad marriage,

32:31.819 --> 32:33.777
trying to make it okay
for the kids.

32:33.821 --> 32:35.692
Right. That was the idea.

32:35.736 --> 32:36.998
And everyone knows that

32:37.042 --> 32:39.000
Russ is kinda rough
around the edges.

32:39.044 --> 32:41.524
Well, I'm gonna make him pay
for what he's done.

32:41.568 --> 32:45.311
But I need someone
who really knows

32:45.354 --> 32:48.662
Betsy and Russ' relationship.

32:48.705 --> 32:51.143
To testify, you mean.

32:51.186 --> 32:53.319
Yeah.

32:53.362 --> 32:56.670
Well, I know everything
about it

32:56.713 --> 32:59.194
'cause Betsy told me.

32:59.238 --> 33:01.196
That's great.

33:01.240 --> 33:04.286
Thank you
for agreeing to testify.

33:04.330 --> 33:07.246
<i>narrator: Sometimes,</i> <i>
it's best to let the fish</i>

33:07.289 --> 33:10.510
<i>think it's catching you.</i>

33:10.553 --> 33:11.990
I was just trying
to help her out.

33:12.033 --> 33:14.514
So when Bets says she wanted
to put my name on policy,

33:14.557 --> 33:17.125
I said,
"Whatever you think is best."

33:17.169 --> 33:21.782
She was like, "Well,
anything's better than Russ."

33:21.825 --> 33:24.045
<i>narrator: Sometimes you cast</i> <i>
so many lines</i>

33:24.089 --> 33:26.178
<i>into that little pond,</i>

33:26.221 --> 33:28.136
<i>it makes a web.</i>

33:28.180 --> 33:30.269
[sighs]

33:30.312 --> 33:32.401
He's not good with money.

33:32.445 --> 33:36.362
Mm. Mm.

33:36.405 --> 33:37.667
I guess Betsy was just like

33:37.711 --> 33:40.279
a lot of women out there,
you know?

33:40.322 --> 33:43.325
Just a bad marriage,

33:43.369 --> 33:45.893
trying to take care
of the kids.

33:45.936 --> 33:48.678
Mm.

33:48.722 --> 33:50.680
Now that's all on me.

33:50.724 --> 33:53.335
Well, I can sort that out
for you.

33:53.379 --> 33:54.554
Oh, no.

33:54.597 --> 33:56.860
- Or--or Tammy can.
- No, I got it.

33:56.904 --> 33:58.601
I can take care of those girls.

33:58.645 --> 34:01.691
Set up a trust for 'em
and everything.

34:01.735 --> 34:04.477
I have been

34:04.520 --> 34:09.395
thanking God for you
every night, Pam.

34:09.438 --> 34:12.093
Don't thank Him for me yet.

34:12.137 --> 34:17.968
I still gotta testify
against Russ.

34:18.012 --> 34:19.492
<i>Well,</i>

34:19.535 --> 34:24.062
Janet was practically
begging me to handle the money.

34:24.105 --> 34:27.935
You know what I had
to do to get it.

34:27.978 --> 34:29.763
Hell and back.

34:29.806 --> 34:32.287
State Acres has this
new phone tree thing.

34:32.331 --> 34:33.941
When you call,
it takes forever.

34:33.984 --> 34:36.987
Finally got an old contact
of mine from HQ, Dusty.

34:37.031 --> 34:39.729
Seems like Dusty's got
bumped up through the ranks.

34:39.773 --> 34:41.601
Totally remembered me too.

34:41.644 --> 34:44.473
"Oh, Pam, how you doing?
How's Mark?"

34:44.517 --> 34:45.953
- That's good.
- Yeah, so, you know.

34:45.996 --> 34:48.651
I said, "Good. Betsy's dead.
Can I get that money?"

34:48.695 --> 34:52.655
And he pulled the trigger
for me right then.

34:52.699 --> 34:54.440
So you're good?

34:54.483 --> 34:56.616
Yeah.

34:58.487 --> 35:00.185
Don't stress about the house.

35:00.228 --> 35:04.537
Get a whole team out there
to kill that mold.

35:04.580 --> 35:07.105
I'll bet you'll get
that facelift

35:07.148 --> 35:09.368
you've been wanting.

35:09.411 --> 35:13.459
Mom, I don't know
what you're even talking about.

35:13.502 --> 35:15.461
Well, your face does.

35:15.504 --> 35:18.333
<i>[unsettling music]</i>

35:18.377 --> 35:19.334
<i>♪</i>

35:19.378 --> 35:22.250
[chuckles]

35:22.294 --> 35:24.252
Oops.

35:24.296 --> 35:29.649
[laughs]

35:32.782 --> 35:38.440
[soft guitar strumming]

35:38.484 --> 35:42.575
So, um, I was able to run
Pam's record one more time.

35:42.618 --> 35:43.576
Came back clean.

35:43.619 --> 35:45.621
♪ We got a spotless queen

35:45.665 --> 35:46.970
It does sound like
she likes to bring on

35:47.014 --> 35:48.624
a lot of lawsuits.

35:48.668 --> 35:50.583
Her neighbors said
Pam talked about suing

35:50.626 --> 35:52.454
the hospital
where her son was born

35:52.498 --> 35:54.891
for giving him cerebral palsy.

35:54.935 --> 35:56.371
Guess that didn't work out.

35:56.415 --> 35:58.330
♪ Hoped to sue for palsy

35:58.373 --> 36:00.158
Then she claimed that
a filing cabinet

36:00.201 --> 36:02.160
fell on her head at work.

36:02.203 --> 36:03.683
♪ Well,
that's pretty ballsy ♪

36:03.726 --> 36:05.163
[chuckles]

36:05.206 --> 36:07.817
♪ Hupp, Hupp, Hupp it up

36:07.861 --> 36:09.950
♪ Hupp, Hupp
- Hey, will you check this out?

36:09.993 --> 36:12.170
[whistling]

36:12.213 --> 36:14.781
<i>[unsettling music]</i>

36:14.824 --> 36:16.783
Is that Leah Askey?

36:16.826 --> 36:18.176
That is Chris Mennemeyer,

36:18.219 --> 36:20.308
who, by the way,
gave out homemade cookies

36:20.352 --> 36:21.962
when she ran
for the judge's seat.

36:22.005 --> 36:25.139
So the judge and Leah Askey
went to high school together?

36:25.183 --> 36:26.836
Should we be worried?

36:26.880 --> 36:28.186
So we had this--

36:28.229 --> 36:29.535
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
There are a lot of things</i>

36:29.578 --> 36:32.059
<i>you could say about Pam Hupp.</i>

36:32.102 --> 36:33.539
<i>A--a ten-year plan.</i>

36:33.582 --> 36:36.324
<i>narrator: One is that</i> <i>
she is cooperative.</i>

36:36.368 --> 36:37.978
Well, the ten-year
turned to 12,

36:38.021 --> 36:40.502
'cause 2008, the bottom
falls out, hits really hard,

36:40.546 --> 36:43.288
so we flip houses on the side
and got plenty of money.

36:43.331 --> 36:44.941
- Okay. It's--
- And a couple of months ago

36:44.985 --> 36:48.206
um, I had to put my mom
in a home and it's pricey.

36:48.249 --> 36:49.598
You know, my mom's got Alzheimer

36:49.642 --> 36:51.339
and dementia and all of that.
- Sure.

36:51.383 --> 36:53.472
That's why
the insurance money

36:53.515 --> 36:55.343
is just sitting there.
I'm too busy.

36:55.387 --> 36:56.866
Of course, I want to set up
that trust though.

36:56.910 --> 36:58.607
Right, right, right, right.
So thanks for coming in

36:58.651 --> 37:00.218
to talk about
the insurance payout.

37:00.261 --> 37:02.220
- Mm-hmm.
- Okay, the 150,000,

37:02.263 --> 37:04.787
that's in a separate account
than your own.

37:04.831 --> 37:11.098
Uh, it's just sitting
in my checking account.

37:11.925 --> 37:14.014
Okay.

37:14.057 --> 37:16.146
We can go to the computer
and pull it up right now.

37:16.190 --> 37:18.279
No, no, no, no. I--

37:18.323 --> 37:20.150
No, no, I'm just saying,

37:20.194 --> 37:24.285
to me, in my world,
150K is not that much.

37:24.329 --> 37:26.809
And if I really,
I mean, I hate to say it,

37:26.853 --> 37:28.420
but if I wanted the money,

37:28.463 --> 37:32.554
my mom is worth half a million
that I get when she dies.

37:32.598 --> 37:35.296
So--and I know that
that sounds--

37:35.340 --> 37:36.602
that sounds morbid
and stuff like that--

37:36.645 --> 37:38.517
So--but you intend
to set up--

37:38.560 --> 37:40.083
I'm her life insurance person.

37:40.127 --> 37:41.128
I know. I know.

37:41.171 --> 37:42.434
But you do intend on

37:42.477 --> 37:44.218
setting up the trust
for Betsy's girls.

37:44.262 --> 37:46.264
Absolutely. Mm-hmm. Yeah.

37:46.307 --> 37:48.091
Just as soon
as we flip this house.

37:48.135 --> 37:49.571
'Cause, you know,
money's tied up

37:49.615 --> 37:52.270
and I still have physical
problems I see doctors for.

37:52.313 --> 37:53.401
It would be good
for you, Pam,

37:53.445 --> 37:55.273
and it'll help
our case against Russ

37:55.316 --> 37:57.449
if that money's no longer
in your possession.

37:57.492 --> 37:59.407
How does it help me exactly?

37:59.451 --> 38:01.061
Well, you know, Schwartz,

38:01.104 --> 38:02.715
he might say you had
something to do with the murder

38:02.758 --> 38:05.979
'cause of a--because
of a financial windfall.

38:06.022 --> 38:07.807
[scoffs]

38:07.850 --> 38:09.330
[sighs]

38:09.374 --> 38:11.332
Here I am trying to help
Betsy's family

38:11.376 --> 38:13.682
on top of my own, and--

38:13.726 --> 38:15.945
What are the possibilities?
I'm sorry for interrupting,

38:15.989 --> 38:18.339
but what are the possibilities
you get this trust set up

38:18.383 --> 38:22.604
for the girls before the trial?

38:22.648 --> 38:24.476
A hundred.

38:24.519 --> 38:28.306
100% it will be set up.

38:28.349 --> 38:31.787
And you'll call me
when you do it?

38:31.831 --> 38:33.354
Yeah, I will.

38:33.398 --> 38:37.227
<i>narrator: That's Pam, working</i> <i>
toward a common goal...</i>

38:37.271 --> 38:38.620
I will.

38:38.664 --> 38:41.580
<i>narrator: Even if</i> <i>
it'll come back to haunt</i>

38:41.623 --> 38:43.973
<i>the Lincoln County</i> <i>
Sheriff's office.</i>

38:44.017 --> 38:46.846
<i>♪</i>

38:48.500 --> 38:50.763
Did Arby's today.

38:50.806 --> 38:52.417
Turns out the timestamp
on the receipt

38:52.460 --> 38:55.333
is when the order was placed,
not received.

38:55.376 --> 38:56.638
Well, there you go.

38:56.682 --> 38:58.727
That adds at least
five minutes to Russ' drive.

38:58.771 --> 38:59.989
There's no way
he could've gotten home

39:00.033 --> 39:01.469
in time to kill Betsy.

39:01.513 --> 39:03.341
Yeah, and I still don't see
any luminol photos

39:03.384 --> 39:06.518
in this latest bundle
from Askey.

39:06.561 --> 39:08.520
So they found Russ'
bloody slippers in the closet,

39:08.563 --> 39:09.956
but no luminol photos to show

39:09.999 --> 39:11.610
that any bloody footprints
were cleaned up.

39:11.653 --> 39:13.525
Nope.

39:13.568 --> 39:16.484
I've been thinking a lot
about these murder slippers.

39:16.528 --> 39:20.270
How they look like
they were dipped in blood.

39:20.314 --> 39:22.838
There's also blood
on Betsy's socks.

39:22.882 --> 39:24.971
Like, why is there blood
on Betsy's socks

39:25.014 --> 39:28.148
if all of the blood loss
is around her neck and arms?

39:28.191 --> 39:29.671
And the socks
are only on halfway,

39:29.715 --> 39:32.021
like someone put them
back on her in a hurry.

39:32.065 --> 39:34.546
They used the sock gloves

39:34.589 --> 39:37.287
to transport
the murder slippers?

39:37.331 --> 39:39.115
Yes?

39:39.159 --> 39:40.943
Right? I play it out.

39:40.987 --> 39:43.381
They take the slippers,
they dip 'em in blood.

39:43.424 --> 39:44.947
They get blood on the socks.

39:44.991 --> 39:46.035
They're in a rush.

39:46.079 --> 39:48.037
They hit the bedroom
light switch,

39:48.081 --> 39:49.996
which is why it looks
like a bloody smear--

39:50.039 --> 39:53.391
And not a fingerprint.

39:53.434 --> 39:56.698
No fingerprints,
no evidence of a cleanup.

39:56.742 --> 39:58.744
But even if Askey says
those luminol photos

39:58.787 --> 40:00.223
didn't turn out,
we still need 'em.

40:00.267 --> 40:01.573
No, I'll stay on her.

40:01.616 --> 40:03.270
And we still need
polygraph results too,

40:03.313 --> 40:05.054
if those even exist.

40:05.098 --> 40:06.882
They said--
you can't fail

40:06.926 --> 40:08.841
a polygraph 100%, right?

40:08.884 --> 40:10.016
It's not a thing.

40:10.059 --> 40:11.583
Well, they can't use it
in court anyway.

40:11.626 --> 40:13.846
And don't forget about
the dozen phone calls

40:13.889 --> 40:15.543
from Pam to Betsy,

40:15.587 --> 40:19.678
but we don't have any records
from Pam's phone, so--

40:19.721 --> 40:21.593
Even without all of that,

40:21.636 --> 40:24.378
we can still prove
he got home too late.

40:24.422 --> 40:27.076
Got his alibi.

40:27.120 --> 40:29.296
We got a SODDI.

40:31.951 --> 40:36.303
[line ringing]

40:37.435 --> 40:39.959
Hey, Russ. How you doing?

40:40.002 --> 40:41.656
<i>Not great.</i>

40:41.700 --> 40:44.093
<i>I haven't heard from my girls.</i>

40:44.137 --> 40:46.139
I mean, radio silence.

40:46.182 --> 40:48.750
It's not like Mariah.

40:48.794 --> 40:50.926
I just--

40:50.970 --> 40:53.233
I want to make things better,
I guess.

40:53.276 --> 40:55.322
<i>Yeah, well, the trial's</i> <i>
right around the corner</i>

40:55.365 --> 40:58.412
and I'm going to make sure
they see the Pam of it. Okay.

40:58.456 --> 41:01.067
And you are gonna
get your girls back

41:01.110 --> 41:03.765
<i>because we got one thing</i> <i>
on our side that they don't,</i>

41:03.809 --> 41:07.987
and it's a luxury that
I'm used to working without.

41:08.030 --> 41:10.032
What's that?

41:10.076 --> 41:12.513
<i>The truth.</i>

41:12.557 --> 41:16.125
<i>narrator: Ah, truth.</i> <i>
A powerful thing.</i>

41:16.169 --> 41:18.780
<i>[upbeat jazzy music]</i>

41:18.824 --> 41:22.958
<i>But can it prevail in</i> <i>
a tight-knit town like Troy?</i>

41:23.002 --> 41:25.352
Schwartz might want to keep
wife killers on the streets,

41:25.395 --> 41:26.832
but by the grace of God,

41:26.875 --> 41:30.183
I am putting this one away.
Whoo!

41:30.226 --> 41:31.445
Cheers to you!

41:31.489 --> 41:38.583
<i>♪</i>

41:42.456 --> 41:44.850
Yes. Yes!

41:44.893 --> 41:46.286
Whoo-hoo!

41:46.329 --> 41:48.549
<i>♪</i>

41:48.593 --> 41:52.858
Hey, let's get this hero
another shot!

41:52.901 --> 41:54.860
<i>♪</i>

41:54.903 --> 41:56.339
Um, sir?

41:56.383 --> 41:57.993
Another Shirley Temple, sir.

41:58.037 --> 41:59.865
Sir? Hello?

41:59.908 --> 42:06.828
<i>♪</i>

42:08.743 --> 42:11.224
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
A tight-knit town indeed.</i>

42:11.267 --> 42:14.227
<i>♪</i>

42:14.270 --> 42:17.230
<i>[sinister music]</i>

42:17.273 --> 42:24.411
<i>♪</i>
